“Functional data is multivariate data with an ordering on the dimensions” (Muller, 2006)

\[y_{ij} = x_i(t_{ij}) + (\epsilon_{ij})\]

  • Conceptually, we regard functional data as being smooth.
  • In practice, functional data are observed at discrete (finite) points.
  • Very Often, functional data are high-dimensional.
  • Time points where observations are taken may not be equally-spaced.

Interests?

  1. Exploration of data characteristics
  • mean, covariance
  • principal components
  1. Relationships of functional data
  • functional regression
  1. Others
  • classification
  • clustering

Difficulties?

  1. Noise
  2. Infinite-dimensional
  3. Interpretation
  4. Theory
  5. \(n<p\) : regularization

Representing functional data as smooth functions

Why?

  1. Data are often noisy.
  2. Data are observed at different sets of points. There is a need to interpolate to a common grid.
  3. Data are not observed at a sparse set of points.

만약, 데이터가 오차 없이 관측되었고, 같은 집합 위에서 충분히 밀도 있게 얻어졌다면, 이 과정은 생략할 수 있다.

There are two popuar approaches

  1. Basis function methods
  2. Smmothing by local weighting

위 두 방법은 비모수함수추정의 대표적인 두 접근방법이다. 이론적인 관점에서는 두 방법 모두 활발히 연구되고 있으나, practical하게는 basis에 근거한 방법이 좀 더 널리 쓰이는 것으로 보인다.

Roughness penalty approach

Assume that there is a single curve

\[y_i = x(t_i) + \epsilon_i\]

다음과 같은 basis expansion을 고려

\[x(t) \approx \sum_{j=1}^K c_j \phi_j(t) \]

다음을 최소화하는 \(c_j\)들을 선택

\[\sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - x(t_i))^2 = \sum_{i=1}^n \left(y_i - \sum_{j=1}^K c_j \phi_j(t_i)\right)^2\]

만약, basis function의 개수를 충분히 많이 선택하면 위 값을 항상 0으로 만드는 게 가능! \(\rightarrow\) \(x(\cdot)\)의 smoothness를 적당히 보장하는 penalty 부여.

Minimize

\[\sum_{i=1}^n (y_i - x(t_i))^2 + \lambda \int [x''(t)]^2 dt\]

Mean function estimation

\[\bar x(t) = n^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^n x_i(t)\]

m_tem = mean.fd(Tem)     # mean function evaluation
plot(Tem,lwd=0.1,col=1,lty="dashed")
## [1] "done"
lines(m_tem$coefs,lwd=2,col=2)

Smoothing may be needed.

Covariance function estimation

\[\sigma(s,t) = n^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^n ( x_i(s) - \bar x(s)) ( x_i(t) - \bar x(t))\]

Smoothing may be needed.

Correlation function estimation

\[\rho(s,t) = \frac{\sigma(s,t)}{\sqrt{\sigma(s,s)}\sqrt{\sigma(t,t)}}\]

2. Functional Principal Component Analysis

Most sets of data display a small number of dominant or substantial modes of variation.

Recall that the notion of PCA in multivariate analysis

Karhunen-Loève decomposition

\[\sigma(s,t) = \sum_{j=1}^\infty d_j \xi_j(s)\xi_j(t)\]

for \(\int \xi_i(t)\xi_j(t)dt = I(i=j)\).

\(d_j\) : eigenvalues & \(\xi_i(\cdot)\) : eigenfunctions

Then,

\[x_i(t) = \bar x (t) + \sum_{j=1}^\infty f_{ij}\xi_j(t)\]

where \(f_{ij}\) are principal component scores defined as

\[f_{ij} = \int \xi_j(t) [x_i(t)-\bar x(t)]dt\]

Note that

  • \(d_i = Var(f_{ij})\)
  • \(d_i/\sum_i d_i\) is proportion of variance explained

Example : Weather data

\[ \bar x(t) \pm c_j\xi_j(t) ~{\rm plots}\]

daytemppcaobj <- pca.fd(daytempfd, nharm=4)   # producing a pca functional object
plot.pca.fd(daytemppcaobj)                    # plotting PC functions

PC functions

plot(daytemppcaobj$harmonics)

## [1] "done"

Smoothing sometimes gives a better result.

Scatterplot for the first 2 PCs

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

3. Funtional linear regression

There are 3 modes

  1. Functional covariate, scalar response : temperature vs rainfall, image vs clinical outcome
  2. Functional covariate, functional response : temparature vs precipitation
  3. scalar covariate, functional response : climate zone vs temparature, diagnosis vs image

Functional linear model for scalar responses

\[y_i = \alpha + \int x_i(t)\beta(t) dt + \epsilon_i\]

Note that this is a natural extension of the ordinary multiple linear regression model.

\[y_i = \alpha+ \sum_{j=1}^p x_{ij} \beta_j + \epsilon_i\]

Estimation?

Since the regression parameter \(\beta(\cdot)\) is infite-dimensional, regularization is necessary.

\[PEN(\beta) = \sum_{i=1}^n \left(y_i - \alpha-\int x_i(t)\beta(t) dt \right)^2 + \lambda \int (\beta''(t))^2 dt\]

Example : Weather data

\[\log(precipitation) \sim temperature(t)\]

annualprec <- log10(apply(CanadianWeather$dailyAv[,,"Precipitation.mm"],2,sum)) # annual precipitation
smallbasis <- create.fourier.basis(c(0, 365), 5,axes=list('axesIntervals'))
tempfd <- smooth.basis(day.5,CanadianWeather$dailyAv[,,"Temperature.C"], smallbasis)$fd
#### do function regression ####
precip.Temp.f <- fRegress(annualprec ~ tempfd)
#### estimated coefficient function ####
plot(precip.Temp.f$betaestlist$tempfd$fd,ylab="beta")

## [1] "done"
  • 2월, 9월 경에 춥거나
  • 5월, 11월 경에 온도가 높으면

연간 강수량이 많아지는 경향이 있다.

Prediction

plot(annualprec,predict(precip.Temp.f),main="Predicted vs observed")
abline(a=0,b=1,col=2)

Functional response model

\[y_i(t) = \beta_0(t) + \sum_{j=1}^p \beta_j(t)x_{ij} + \epsilon_i(t)\]

각 fixed \(t\)에서 linear model을 적합할 수 있다. 하지만, 적당한 smoothness penalty를 고려한다면,

Minimize

\[\sum_{i=1}^n \int ( y_i(t) - \hat y_i(t) )^2 dt + \sum_{j=1}^p \lambda_j \int (\beta_j''(t))^2 dt\]

Example : Weather data

\[temperature(t) \sim region\]

daybasis65 <- create.fourier.basis(rangeval=c(0, 365), nbasis=65,
axes=list('axesIntervals'))
Temp.fd <- with(CanadianWeather, smooth.basisPar(day.5,
dailyAv[,,'Temperature.C'], daybasis65)$fd)
TempRgn.f <- fRegress(Temp.fd ~ region, CanadianWeather)
par(mfrow=c(1,4))
plot(TempRgn.f$betaestlist$const$fd,ylim=c(-30,30),main="Arctic")    # beta_0
## [1] "done"
plot(TempRgn.f$betaestlist$region.Atlantic$fd,ylim=c(-30,30),main="Atlantic-Arctic")   # beta_1
## [1] "done"
plot(TempRgn.f$betaestlist$region.Continental$fd,ylim=c(-30,30),main="Continental-Arctic")  # beta_2
## [1] "done"
plot(TempRgn.f$betaestlist$region.Pacific$fd,ylim=c(-30,30),main="Pacific-Arctic")  # beta_3

## [1] "done"

Functional response model : Concurrent Linear Model

\[y_i(t) = \beta_0(t) + \sum_{j=1}^p \beta_j(t)x_{ij}(t) + \epsilon_i(t)\]

Example : gait cycle

Gait cycle for hip and knee angle while walking

\[knee(t) \sim hip(t)\]

plot(gait[,1, 1], gait[, 1, 2], type="b",xlab="Hip",ylab="Knee")

Smoothed data

(gaittime <- as.numeric(dimnames(gait)[[1]])*20)
##  [1]  0.5  1.5  2.5  3.5  4.5  5.5  6.5  7.5  8.5  9.5 10.5 11.5 12.5 13.5
## [15] 14.5 15.5 16.5 17.5 18.5 19.5
gaitrange <- c(0,20)
gaitbasis <- create.fourier.basis(gaitrange, nbasis=21)
#### Smoothing by using a user-specified penalty ####
gaitfd <- smooth.basisPar(gaittime, gait,gaitbasis, lambda=1e-2)$fd   
hipfd <- gaitfd[,1]
kneefd <- gaitfd[,2]
par(mfrow=c(2,1))
plot(hipfd)
## [1] "done"
plot(kneefd)

Estimated coefficient functions

knee.hip.f <- fRegress(kneefd ~ hipfd)

  • \(\hat\beta_1\)으로부터 hip이 더 많이 굽혀질 수록 무릎도 더 많이 굽혀지는 경향이 있음을 볼 수 있다.

Functional response : most general model

\[y_i(t) = \beta_0(t) + \int \beta(s,t)x_{i}(s)ds + \epsilon_i(t)\]
